<font color="#FF0000">GI MOVEMENT</font><br>
<tt>Mon Dec  9  0:01:02 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I hate the way Hollywood and even the history books have rewritten what actually happened between GI's and the anti-war movement.  The stereotype is that the protesters spent alot of time booing and spitting at returning GIs.  But I was part of the GI anti-war movement, and remember really good things happening for GIs in the antiwar movement.  There was support for GIs (men and women) who wanted to get their heads together and get out of the military machine.  There were coffeehouses in towns close to bootcamps where servicemen and women could come to talk, put out newspapers, and figure out how to help end the war.  The enemy then was the top brass and the policy-makers in Washington who continued the killing.  But the anti-war folks, civilian and military, got along just fine.  Does anyone else reading this remember the GI movement and the coffeehouses?  Why is none of this ever reflected in the media and movies today?
